Wash down and Overburden from Above Terraces and Settlement
Phase XII: Use levels, robbing and abandonments continue. Upper levels of fluvial wash are deposited. Rooms A and B are abandoned.
Locus 6 squatters’ settlement and Locus 8 burn layer.
Previously abutted the overburden of Trench 77, 2000.
31.20 m in length-by- 6.45 m in width.

Locus 5 represents the accumulation and fill of centuries worth of destruction from the hillsides above whose treacherous terracing were also destroyed by a series of seismic and natural events. The soil color was Dark Reddish Brown (Munsell 5 YR 3/4). Bereft of meaningful contextual artifacts but still rich with an accumulation of artifactual debris, it was mainly excavated by mechanical equipment and backhoes. Of note, however, were original construction materials such as wood beams that were badly damaged which justifies the reconstruction and consolidation of Locus 1 the south wall of the Great Temple. Large ashlars were badly damaged and most likely fell from the terraces to the south rather than the temple proper. Very few architectural fragments especially those associated with the structure seem to have accumulated. However, the lovely sculpted foot of a marble statue that was found against Loci 1 and 3 the south wall of the Great Temple and the central blocked doorway was an especially welcome surprise.
Phase XIII: Major collapses continue into the Islamic period.
Closing Elevation: - 4.09 m or 906.798 m at Sub datum A, and -4.06 m or 906.780 m at Sub datum B.

Phase XI: Further collapse post-CE 5th c., possibly the result of the earthquake of 512. Fill accumulates following the disuse of the canalization systems. The remains of two bodies are found in the upper level fluvial deposits. Localized burning in some areas.
